Your requirement seems to be to find numbers which are surrounded on both sides by either whitespace, or the start/end of the string.  We can use the following pattern:

    (?&lt;!\S)[+-]?\d+(?!\S)

Java code:

&lt;!-- language: java --&gt;

    String input = &quot;123 +234 -345 456 - + abc a+78 sdf-sdf +1abc -3sbc&quot;;
    String pattern = &quot;(?&lt;!\\S)[+-]?\\d+(?!\\S)&quot;;
    Pattern r = Pattern.compile(pattern);
    Matcher m = r.matcher(input);
    List&lt;String&gt; matches = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();
    while (m.find()) {
        matches.add(m.group());
    }
    System.out.println(matches);  // [123, +234, -345, 456]

The regex pattern used here says to match:

 - `(?&lt;!\S)` assert that what precedes be either whitespace or the start of the input
 - `[+-]?` match optional leading +/-
 - `\d+` match an integer number
 - `(?!\S)` assert that what follows be either whitespace or the end of the input

You can leverage programming to make the regex bit simpler. So, you can split the string by space and try to match the pattern for each split value instead of matching the whole input.

The regex will be:

1. `^[-+]?` - It may start with + or -
2. `[0-9]+$` - It is then followed by number till the end

So, the final regex is: `^[-+]?[0-9]+$`

Simple java code will be:

    List&lt;String&gt; result = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();
    String[] arr= &quot;123 +234 -345 456 - + abc a+78 sdf-sdf +1abc -3sbc&quot;.split(&quot; &quot;);
    for(String elem:arr){
        String pattern = &quot;^[-+]?[0-9]+$&quot;;
        Pattern r = Pattern.compile(pattern);
        Matcher m = r.matcher(elem);
        if(m.find()){
           result.add(m.group());
        }
    }

