I&#39;ve been making a Java program which involves manipulating a collection of dynamically created, heterogeneously-typed data stored in a container, and I&#39;ve been running into the following small conundrum which, while I&#39;ve tried to get around it with hacks before, have never felt very satisfied with them.

In the GUI part of the program, we must present the data to the user. When it comes across a field with a given type, it needs to produce a view for data of that type. To make it extensible (Open/Closed Principle) to new types of data without modifying the GUI window class and instead just adding new handler objects to produce new kinds of views, my GUI class has a member like this:

    private HashMap&lt;Class&lt;?&gt;, IViewGenerator&lt;?&gt;&gt; mViewGenerators;

where the ``IViewGenerator&lt;T&gt;`` is an interface to an object which generates view for data of type ``T``, a generic interface:

    interface IViewGenerator&lt;T&gt; {
         View generate(T val); // generic method
    }

This way, I can call a &quot;``addViewGenerator``&quot; method or the like on the GUI object to add new value type support by composition and thus in an &quot;open/closed&quot; fashion.

The problem is this. In the same class as ``mViewGenerators`` we&#39;ll have something like

    private void buildView() {
